SIMPLE: denomination
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Denomination
<hw>De*nom`i*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>denominatio</ets> metonymy: cf. F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧nomination</ets> a
naming.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of naming or
designating.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That by which anything is denominated or styled; an
epithet; a name, designation, or title; especially, a general name
indicating a class of like individuals; a category; <as>as, the
<ex>denomination</ex> of units, or of thousands, or of fourths, or of
shillings, or of tons</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those [qualities] which are classed under the
<qex>denomination</qex> of sublime.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A class, or society of individuals, called by the
same name; a sect; <as>as, a <ex>denomination</ex> of
Christians</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Name; appellation; title. See
<er>Name</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Denominational</ent>⟦br⟧
